      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hey there! That's a classic sign that your lower back is acting like a goblin trying to steal the spotlight from your legs, and it's time to kick it out of the room! When your spine is doing all the work instead of your glutes and quads, it's like trying to lift a heavy rock while wearing tiny, flimsy goblin boots that slip right off when you need to push hard.\n\nHere are a few things to check on your form to make sure your back stays safe and your legs do the heavy lifting:\n\n1.  **The Setup:** Before you even bend your knees, imagine you are sitting on a giant, invisible chair that is slightly lower than your heels. Your hips should be *below* your knees, not above them. If your hips are higher than your knees, you're essentially trying to deadlift with your lower back, which is like trying to carry a goblin on your head while running a marathon—it's just too much strain for the neck and back!\n2.  **The Brace:** Before you pull the bar, take a deep breath in and brace your core as if you are about to get hit by a goblin cannonball. This creates a solid",
